		<item>
		<title>Your next desktop could be a 21.5-inch Android tablet from HP</title>
		<link>http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/everything/~3/293GSY5r0JM/</link>
		<comments>http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/06/your-next-desktop-could-be-a-21-5-inch-android-tablet-from-hp/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 24 Jun 2013 14:19:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Andrew Cunningham</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Gear & Gadgets]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[android]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[HP]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://arstechnica.com/?p=294767</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[You said you wanted options, right?]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="rss-wrap">
<div>
      <img src="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/slate21.jpg"><div class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em">
			<div class="caption-text">HP continues to experiment with Android in places you wouldn't normally find Android.</div>
	
			<div class="caption-credit">
							HP				</div>
	  </div>
  </div>
 <p>You've got an Android phone, an Android tablet, and maybe even an Android laptop, but be honest with yourself: your affection for Google's mobile operating system knows no bounds, and you won't rest until it's powering literally every computer you own. If this description fits you, HP's newly announced Slate 21 is for you. It's a 21.5-inch, 1920×1080 kickstand-toting all-in-one equipped with Nvidia's Tegra 4 SoC and running Android 4.2.2.</p>
<p>We don't know much more about the all-in-one, which was announced this morning at an HP event in Beijing, but according to Engadget's <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/06/24/hp-launches-slate-21-aio/">translated version of the press release</a>, it also includes an HD webcam, integrated speakers, and HP's <a href="http://www.hp.com/global/us/en/wireless/wireless-direct.html">Wireless Direct</a> printing tech. We don't know anything about pricing, availability, or whether the desktop will even come to the US, but CNET <a href="http://asia.cnet.com/hp-slate-21-aio-is-a-21-inch-android-tablet-62221673.htm?src=twt">reports</a> that it will be rolled out to multiple countries eventually.</p>
<p>Perhaps in an effort to offer cheaper machines without expensive Windows licenses or Intel processors, the PC OEMs are increasingly beginning to experiment with Android in form factors one wouldn't normally expect. The HP Slate 21 follows the previously announced <a href="http://www8.hp.com/us/en/ads/x2/slatebook-x2.html">HP Slate x2</a> convertible laptop, which is itself reminiscent of Asus' long-running <a href="http://eee.asus.com/en/transformer-300/features">Transformer Pad</a> series. Asus is also responsible for a few other Android-equipped curios, including both an <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/03/asus-1299-transformer-all-in-one-dual-wields-windows-8-and-android/">all-in-one computer</a> and an <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/06/two-cpus-two-batteries-two-oses-asus-announces-transformer-book-trio/">upcoming laptop</a> that have full Android tablets inside their detachable screens.</p>
</div><p><a href="http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/06/your-next-desktop-could-be-a-21-5-inch-android-tablet-from-hp/">Read on Ars Technica</a> | <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/06/your-next-desktop-could-be-a-21-5-inch-android-tablet-from-hp/?comments=1">Comments</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/everything/~4/293GSY5r0JM" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
