		<title>Heirs of Infocom: Where interactive fiction authors and games stand today</title>
		<link>http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/everything/~3/f5VxBEVRMGk/</link>
		<comments>http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/06/heirs-of-infocom-where-interactive-fiction-authors-and-games-stand-today/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 23 Jun 2013 18:00:54 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Jeremy Reimer</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Opposable Thumbs]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[gaming]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://arstechnica.com/?p=294239</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Mobile devices are helping authors present their stories to a new audience.]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="rss-wrap">
<div style="float:right top">
      <img src="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/infocom-article-300.jpg"><div class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em">
			<div class="caption-text">Andrew Plotkin, Muffy Berlyn and Michael Berlyn await their release from The Lamp</div>
	
			<div class="caption-credit">
							<a rel="nofollow" href="http://getlamp.com">Jason Scott</a>
				</div>
	  </div>
  </div>
 <p>In my <a title="Get Lamp Review" href="http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2010/09/the-great-thing-about/">review of <em>Get Lamp</em></a>, the documentary about text adventures, I mentioned that the original Infocom employees believed the market for these games could exist for hundreds of years. After all, the novel is still around today and, despite stiff competition from movies and video games, writing fiction is still a profitable endeavor. Why not interactive fiction?</p>
<p>The reality, however, is that since the demise of Infocom in 1989, many people have tried to make interactive fiction into a commercial endeavor. None have been able to figure out how to make the financial side work—until recently. Everything changed with the rise of smartphones and tablets.</p>
<h2>A new platform, a new type of game</h2>
<p>Michael Berlyn was an “implementor” at Infocom in the early 1980s and was responsible for hit games such as <em>Suspended</em> and <em>Infidel</em>. He left the company in 1984 before it imploded and went on to a successful career in game design and consulting. Berlyn created the <em>Bubsy</em> side-scrolling games on the Sega Genesis and contributed to <em>Syphon Filter</em> on the original PlayStation. He later retired from the industry and moved to Florida with his wife, Muffy. But when he saw the first iPhone, he knew there was a chance to create something new.</p>
</div><p><a href="http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/06/heirs-of-infocom-where-interactive-fiction-authors-and-games-stand-today/#p3">Read 8 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/06/heirs-of-infocom-where-interactive-fiction-authors-and-games-stand-today/?comments=1">Comments</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/everything/~4/f5VxBEVRMGk" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/06/heirs-of-infocom-where-interactive-fiction-authors-and-games-stand-today/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		<feedburner:origLink>http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/06/heirs-of-infocom-where-interactive-fiction-authors-and-games-stand-today/</feedburner:origLink></item>
		<item>
		<title>Startup gives farmers shot at fair prices, market access via text messages</title>
		<link>http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/everything/~3/VdkhWEs0sOY/</link>
		<comments>http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/06/startup-uses-sms-to-give-farmers-shot-at-fair-prices-market-access/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 23 Jun 2013 17:00:14 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>WIRED UK</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Ministry of Innovation]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[africa]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[agriculture]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[farming]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[MFarm]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[SMS]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://arstechnica.com/?p=294195</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Kenyan farmers were "oppressed for decades and disconnected in terms of information."]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="rss-wrap">
<div>
      <img src="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/farmers2-640x426.jpg"><div class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em">
	
			<div class="caption-credit">
							MFarm				</div>
	  </div>
  </div>
 <p>For many low-volume Kenyan farmers, the only source of information about the market rate for crops comes from the very people who are trying to buy them. The lack of pricing transparency means that farmers don't always get the best deal. <a href="http://mfarm.co.ke/about">MFarm</a> seeks to solve this problem by providing up-to-date market prices via an app or SMS direct to farmers. It also connects farmers with buyers directly, cutting out the middlemen.</p>
<p>MFarm's CEO is Jamila Abass, a 29-year-old computer scientist from Kenya. She founded MFarm in 2010 after reading about how farmers have been "oppressed for decades and disconnected in terms of information."</p>
<p>"Many farmers only have the produce but don't have the means to market their produce themselves," Abass told Wired.co.uk. "They have to rely on middlemen who show up and give them both the price and the buyer. They have no information and no alternative market. We wanted to close that information gap between the farmers and the market."</p>
</div><p><a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/06/startup-uses-sms-to-give-farmers-shot-at-fair-prices-market-access/#p3">Read 18 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/06/startup-uses-sms-to-give-farmers-shot-at-fair-prices-market-access/?comments=1">Comments</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/everything/~4/VdkhWEs0sOY" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/06/startup-uses-sms-to-give-farmers-shot-at-fair-prices-market-access/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		<feedburner:origLink>http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/06/startup-uses-sms-to-give-farmers-shot-at-fair-prices-market-access/</feedburner:origLink></item>
