		<pubDate>Sat, 22 Jun 2013 22:15:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Megan Geuss</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Opposable Thumbs]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[particle physics]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[XBox]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://arstechnica.com/?p=294457</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[We also talk about Microsoft's Xbox policy reversal.]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="rss-wrap">
<div>
      <img src="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/belle_rolled_in_hires_big-640x425.jpg"><div class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em">
			<div class="caption-text">The Belle detector at Japan's KEK facility.</div>
	
			<div class="caption-credit">
							<a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.ekp.kit.edu/english/belle.php">Karlsruhe Institute of Technology</a>
				</div>
	  </div>
  </div>
 <p>Ever since <em>The Guardian</em> leaked a top secret court order allowing the National Security Agency (NSA) to collect the telephone metadata belonging to all Verizon customers, daily, for a period of three months, more and more has been revealed about the way the NSA works and how it gathers information. The most recent information comes from a document called "Minimization Procedures Used by the National Security Agency in Connection with Acquisitions of Foreign Intelligence." It reveals that the NSA will retain anonymized and encrypted e-mail and instant messages, whether or not the messages come from people within the US.</p>
<p>Dan Goodin gave us all the details in his article <b><a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/06/use-of-tor-and-e-mail-crypto-could-increase-chances-that-nsa-keeps-your-data/">Use of Tor and e-mail crypto could increase chances that NSA keeps your data</a></b>. Naturally Ars commenters, no strangers to using Tor and encryption in their e-mails, had strong opinions on this topic.</p>
<p><a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/06/use-of-tor-and-e-mail-crypto-could-increase-chances-that-nsa-keeps-your-data/?comments=1&amp;post=24755031#comment-24755031"><strong>theblop</strong></a> wrote, "It seems the main issue in the news about the NSA data collection always revolves around whether US citizen are being monitored or not. Well, here, outside the US, we are now 100 percent sure that we are being monitored by the US since we all use Google, Facebook, etc... Isn't that a much bigger story?" <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/06/use-of-tor-and-e-mail-crypto-could-increase-chances-that-nsa-keeps-your-data/?comments=1&amp;post=24755591#comment-24755591"><strong>DeeAaaKay</strong></a> clarified:</p>
</div><p><a href="http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/06/a-privacy-paradox-and-a-peculiar-particle-ars-readers-react/#p3">Read 10 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href="http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/06/a-privacy-paradox-and-a-peculiar-particle-ars-readers-react/?comments=1">Comments</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/everything/~4/B3o6kfULl_E" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/06/a-privacy-paradox-and-a-peculiar-particle-ars-readers-react/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
